            <![CDATA[
                    <p><img src="https://seyb.github.io/seyb-notes/media/posts/1/Capture-decran-2022-12-15-a-12.14.59.png" class="type:primaryImage" alt="A person trying to catch flying glass bulbs with the text &quot;let&#x27;s capture ideas&quot;" /></p>
                
  <p>
    At the beginning of December I attended the <a href="https://www.bdxio.fr/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">BDX.IO</a> conferences where I rediscovered sketchnoting. I had some practices on it a few years ago but had almost left it mostly because I lacked in organizing my notes.&nbsp;
  </p>

    <figure class="blockquote">
      <blockquote><strong>Sketchnotes</strong> are rich visual notes created from a mix of handwriting, drawings, hand-lettering, shapes, and visual elements like arrows, boxes, and lines.&nbsp;</blockquote>
      <figcaption>Mike Rohde</figcaption>
    </figure>

  <p>
    To have a fresh reboot, I decided to add some constraints: I am now using a Remarkable e-paper tablet, great for taking and organizing my notes but has a limited set of colour.&nbsp;
  </p>
